snippet.textDisplay:
While it looks somewhat interesting,it looks like they are trying way too hard to make a political statement through the show rather than build an intricate and intriguing plot. Of course, we are only seeing a very small fraction of what is to come.
From my perspective, it feels too bright. The gothic sense or feeling of dread is missing. The period of time feels odd in comparison to what this show should bring. I kindof feel like they should have pushed the timeline back, but use the same culture base. Just reduce the amount of technology. Making it a period piece, just a cultural period piece. It feels like it's too advanced from what a Penny Dreadful should be.

snippet.textDisplay: I am so excited. I understand the people missing Vanessa ives but I feel like the show did what it set out to do and did what very few shows do these days. John Logan, creator and writer of the series, planned for three seasons, very much like a typical three act play. The conclusion, for me, was so good and I miss Vanessa Ives but I feel like I miss her like Ethan and Malcolm will miss her. I grew to love her character and when her suffering was ended, I cried. Because I will miss her but also she is finally free. As for his upcoming season, I have faith in John Logan and his vision for this story. A showdown between two supernatural entities with the City of Angels caught in the middle, during a very chaotic time in old LA (Black Dahlia, anyone?) I am SO excited to watch Nathan Lane and Natalie Dormer in particular and I hope the fans give this show a chance.

snippet.textDisplay: To me, Penny Dreadful was (almost, because it failed in some ways) the series that The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen film should have been. Pretty decent cast / team: Quartermain, a gun - slinging werewolf named Talbot (loved that nod to Lon Chaney), etc. This new series should also have it’s own supporting cast of (1930’s?) literary & classic film heroes and monsters. Much like (Well, EXACTLY like) Alan Moore’s comic- book series, Ives was somehow able to live through the Ages without aging. I wonder which other Extraordinary Gantlemen / Women from that era they should be using?

snippet.textDisplay: Reminds me of "Carnivàle" - which is a good thing (the show was so way ahead of its time) - and I love me some Natalie Dorner. Guessing that the trailer keeps some of the show's secrets and in the end it will also be a menagerie of different mythical and literary "heroes". Calling it "Penny Dreadful" is a little stupid, because the term is so inextricably linked with the UK and the 19th century... maybe Natalie Dormer is older than she looks in the series and made her way from London to the U.S. as an immigrant.
